@comment
@comment Exercise 2.2 In General
@comment
@sc{solution} In general,
since we are using sum-of-products form, create the minterms for each
row of the truth table. Each minterm is a product (AND) of the inputs which
is TRUE for that row. The Boolean equation is the sum (OR) of each minterm.
@*@*
@comment
@comment Exercise 2.2 Part A
@comment
@sc{solution} @math{(a)}
Create the minterms for each row of the truth table in @ref{fig281} @math{(a)}.
@tex
$$
\vbox{\offinterlineskip
    \halign{\quad$#$&\strut\quad$#$\quad&\vrule#&\quad$#$\quad&\vrule#&\quad#\quad&\vrule#&#\quad\cr
    A & B && Y &&minterm&\quad name\cr
    \noalign{\hrule}
    &\omit&height2pt&\omit&height2pt&\omit&height2pt&\cr
    0 & 0 && 0 && $\overline{A}\overline{B}$&\quad$m_0$\cr
    0 & 1 && 1 && $\overline{A}B$&\quad$m_1$\cr
    1 & 0 && 1 && $A\overline{B}$&\quad$m_2$\cr
    1 & 1 && 1 && $AB$&\quad$m_3$\cr
    }
}
$$
@end tex
The Boolean equation in sum-of-products form is the sum of the minterms for
which the output @math{Y} is @math{TRUE}.

This yields:
@tex
$$\eqalign{
    Y &= m_1 + m_2 + m_3\cr
    Y &= \overline{A}B + A\overline{B} + AB}
