@*@*
@sc{exercise 2.6} Minimize each of the Boolean equations from Exercise 2.2.
@comment
@comment In General
@comment
@*@*
@sc{solution} In general, cleverly apply the Axioms of Boolean Algebra and the
Boolean theorems of one and several variables to simplify the canonical
sum-of-product.Boolean equations created in Exercise 2.2.
@comment
@comment Exercise 2.6 Part A
@comment
@*@*
@sc{solution} @math{(a)}
Minimize the equation from Exercise 2.2 @math{(a)}:
@tex
$$Y = \overline{A}\,B + A\,\overline{B} + A\,B$$
@end tex
We can see from the truth table in @ref{fig281} (a) that the Boolean function
is an OR so we know that the result must be
@tex
$$Y = A + B$$
@end tex
Restate the equation:
@tex
$$\eqalign{
Y &= \overline{A}\,B + A\,\overline{B} + A\,B\cr
  &= \overline{A}\,B + (A\,B + A\,\overline{B})
}$$
@end tex
Here we can apply T10:
@tex
$$\eqalign{
Y &= \overline{A}\,B + A
}$$
@end tex
But, since T10 is merely an application of theorems T8 and T5', we can also
do this:
@tex
$$\eqalign{
Y &= \overline{A}\,B + (A\,B + A\,\overline{B})\cr
  &= \overline{A}\,B + A\bullet(\overline{B} + B)\cr
  &= \overline{A}\,B + A\bullet1\cr
Y &= \overline{A}\,B + A
}$$
@end tex
In either approach we find the same result. Applying theorem T6':
@tex
$$
Y = A + \overline{A}\,B
$$
@end tex
But we know that the Boolean function is just @math{A + B} so this is not
minimized yet. We can use the expanding trick and apply theorems T2', T1, and
T10, Null Element, Identity, and Combining:
@tex
$$\eqalign{
Y &= A\bullet(B + 1) + \overline{A}\,B\cr
  &= A\,B + A + \overline{A}\,B\cr
  &= A + A\,B + \overline{A}\,B\cr
  &= A + (B\,A + B\,\overline{A})\cr
Y &= A + B
}$$
@end tex
Now the Boolean equation is fully minimized.

Note this exercise. We will refer to is in later exercises that contain
expressions of the form
@math{\overline{A}\,B + A\,\overline{B} + A\,B}. This can be expressed as our
own personal theorem:
@tex
$$A\,B + A\,\overline{B} + \overline{A}\,B = A + B$$
@end tex
A variation on this may also be useful to reference later:
@tex
$$A + \overline{A}\,B = A + B$$
@end tex
@tex
\hskip1.5in\vbox{\hrule width3in}
@end tex
@comment
@comment Exercise 2.6 Part B
@comment
@*@*
@sc{solution} @math{(b)}
Minimize the equation from Exercise 2.2 @math{(b)}:

@tex
$$\eqalign{
    Y &= \overline{A}\,\overline{B}\,C +
         \overline{A}\,B\,\overline{C} +
         \overline{A}\,B\,C +
         A\,\overline{B}\,\overline{C} +
         A\,B\,\overline{C}\cr
}$$
@end tex
Begin by rewriting the equation. Factor some common literals:
@tex
$$\eqalign{
Y &= \overline{A}\bullet(\overline{B}\,C + B\,\overline{C} + B\,C) +
     A\bullet(\overline{B}\,\overline{C} + B\,\overline{C})\cr
  &= \overline{A}\bullet(B\,C + B\,\overline{C} + \overline{B}\,C) +
     A\bullet(\overline{C}\,B + \overline{C}\,\overline{B})\cr
}$$
@end tex
Recognize that the two terms in parenthesis can be minimized using the
expression derived in Exercise 2.6 @math{(a)} and theorem T10.
@tex
$$\eqalign{
B\,C + B\,\overline{C} + \overline{B}\,C &= B + C\cr
\overline{C}\,B + \overline{C}\,\overline{B} &= \overline{C}
}$$
@end tex
So we can continue by substituting these minimized expressions:
@tex
$$\eqalign{
Y &= \overline{A}\bullet(B + C) + A\bullet(\overline{C})\cr
Y &= \overline{A}\,B + \overline{A}\,C + A\,\overline{C}
}$$
@end tex
There is an alternate solution. We can approach the minimization just a bit
differently and reach a different solution that is logically equivalent.
@tex
$$\eqalign{
Y &= \overline{A}\,\overline{B}\,C +
     \overline{A}\,B\,\overline{C} +
     \overline{A}\,B\,C +
     A\,\overline{B}\,\overline{C} +
     A\,B\,\overline{C}\cr
  &= \overline{A}\bullet(\overline{B}\,C + B\,C) +
     A\,\overline{B}\,\overline{C} +
     B\,\overline{C}\bullet(A + \overline{A})\cr
}$$
@end tex
We can apply theorems T10 and T5' to the expressions in parenthesis:
@tex
$$\eqalign{
B\,C + \overline{B}\,C &= C\cr
A + \overline{A} &= 1
}$$
@end tex
Continuing@dots{}
@tex
$$\eqalign{
Y &= \overline{A}\bullet(C) + A\,\overline{B}\,\overline{C} +
     B\,\overline{C}\bullet(1)\cr
  &= \overline{A}\,C + A\,\overline{B}\,\overline{C} + B\,\overline{C}\cr
}$$
@end tex
The equation needs an additional term so we can minimize further. Using the
Null Element theorem, T2', we can expand the expression:
@tex
$$\eqalign{
Y &= \overline{A}\,C + A\,\overline{B}\,\overline{C} +
     B\,\overline{C}\bullet(A + 1)\cr
  &= \overline{A}\,C + A\,\overline{B}\,\overline{C} +
     A\,B\,\overline{C} + B\,\overline{C}\cr
  &= \overline{A}\,C + A\bullet(\overline{B}\,\overline{C} + B\,\overline{C}) +
     B\,\overline{C}\cr
}$$
@end tex
Since the Combining theorem T10 tells us that
@math{\overline{B}\,\overline{C} + B\,\overline{C} = \overline{C}}, we can
further simplify:
@tex
$$\eqalign{
Y &= \overline{A}\,C + A\bullet(\overline{C}) + B\,\overline{C}\cr
Y &= \overline{A}\,C + A\,\overline{C} + B\,\overline{C}
}$$
@end tex
That is the alternate and logically equivalent result.
@*
@tex
