@comment Exercise 2.6 Part D
@comment
@*@*
@sc{solution} @math{(d)}
Minimize the equation from Exercise 2.2 @math{(d)}:
@tex
$$\eqalign{
Y &= \overline{A}\,\overline{B}\,\overline{C}\,\overline{D} +
     \overline{A}\,\overline{B}\,C\,\overline{D} +
     \overline{A}\,\overline{B}\,C\,D + \overline{A}\,B\,C\,\overline{D} +
     \overline{A}\,B\,C\,D + A\,\overline{B}\,\overline{C}\,\overline{D}\cr
  &+ A\,\overline{B}\,C\,\overline{D}}$$
@end tex
Use theorems T6--T8, Commutativity, Associativity, and Distributivity to
rewrite the equation:
@tex
$$\eqalign{
Y &= \overline{B}\,\overline{C}\,\overline{D}\bullet(A + \overline{A}) +
     C\,\overline{D}\bullet(\overline{A}\,B + A\,\overline{B} + \overline{A}\,\overline{B}) +
     C\,D\bullet(\overline{A}\,\overline{B} + \overline{A}\,B)\cr
}$$
@end tex
Use theorems T5', Complements, T10, Combining, and the relationship established
in Exercise 2.6 @math{(a)}:
@tex
$$\eqalign{
A + \overline{A} &= 1\cr
A\,B + A\,\overline{B} + \overline{A}\,B &= A + B\cr
B\,C + B\overline{C} &= B
}$$
@end tex
Now simplify the equation:
@tex
$$\eqalign{
Y &= \overline{B}\,\overline{C}\,\overline{D}\bullet(1) +
     C\,\overline{D}(\overline{A} + \overline{B}) + C\,D\bullet(\overline{A})\cr
  &= \overline{B}\,\overline{C}\,\overline{D} + \overline{A}\,C\,\overline{D} +
     \overline{B}\,C\,\overline{D} + \overline{A}\,C\,D\cr
  &= \overline{B}\,\overline{C}\,\overline{D} + \overline{B}\,C\,\overline{D} +
     \overline{A}\,C\,\overline{D} + \overline{A}\,C\,D\cr
}$$
@end tex
Again, use theorems T6--T8, and T5' to rewrite the equation:
@tex
$$\eqalign{
Y &= \overline{B}\,\overline{D}\bullet(C + \overline{C}) +
     \overline{A}\,C\bullet(D + \overline{D})\cr
  &= \overline{B}\,\overline{D}\bullet(1) + \overline{A}\,C\bullet(1)\cr
  &= \overline{B}\,\overline{D} + \overline{A}\,C\cr
Y &= \overline{A}\,C + \overline{B}\,\overline{D}
}$$
@end tex
Undoubtedly there are many ways to approach this. Some may be more difficult
that others because of the expressions encountered along the way. Some are more
difficult than others to minimize.

Check the result using @emph{perfect induction} against the truth table in
@ref{fig281} @math{(d)}. Note that this does not necessarily indicate that the
result is fully minimized, only that there have been no algebraic erros in
arriving at the result.
